ST:STUDY_TITLE                   	periodontal inflammatory status
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	Onset of chronic periodontitis is associated with an aberrant polymicrobial
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	community, termed dysbiosis. Findings of a recent model of its etiology
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	suggested that dysbiosis holds a conserved metabolic signature as an emergent
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	property. The purpose of this study was to identify robust biomarkers for
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	periodontal inflammation severity. Furthermore, we investigated
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	disease-associated metabolic signatures of periodontal microbiota using a
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	salivary metabolomics approach. Collection of whole saliva samples was performed
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	before and after removal of supragingival plaque (debridement). Periodontal
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	inflamed surface area (PISA) was employed as an indicator of periodontal
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	inflammatory status. Based on multivariate analyses using pre-debridement
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	salivary metabolomics data, we found that the metabolites associated with higher
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	PISA included cadaverine and hydrocinnamate, while uric acid and ethanolamine
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	were associated with lower PISA. Next, we focused on dental plaque metabolic
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	byproducts by selecting significantly decreased salivary metabolites following
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	debridement. Metabolite set enrichment analysis revealed that polyamine
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	metabolism, arginine and proline metabolism, butyric acid metabolism, and lysine
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	degradation were distinctive metabolic signatures of dental plaque in the high
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	PISA group, which may have relevance to the metabolic signatures of
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	disease-associated communities. Collectively, our findings identified potential
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	biomarkers of periodontal inflammatory status, while they also provide insight
ST:STUDY_SUMMARY                 	into metabolic signatures of dysbiotic communities.
